<br>
Personally, I prefer to use painter for my outlines rather then doing it by hand. For one thing, the lines are a lot smoother, and if you mess up, you can always go back and fix it.<br>
<br>
First, scan in your lineart in photoshop. Don't scan it in Painter, because for one thing, it doesn't give you as good of a scan as you can get in photoshop. <br>
<br>
Now then, after you've cropped your picture down to just the character, copy the picture on to another layer, erase the original background, go to the channels option and hit the little channels button on the bottom (make sure that you've selected your original sketch). Now then, after you've hit delete and deselect, go to the layers folder, hit preserve transparency and select a dark blue or purple (or any other color you want, just as long as it's dark and NOT black.) Take a big brush and go over the sketch so that it's in the new color. <br>
<br>
Once you're done changing the color of the sketch, go up to edit -&gt; image size. Change the image size to 200%. Why are we working so big? First of all, you'll be able to get more detail into the lineart, and second of all, you'll be able to vary the widths of the lines more. Save what you have done as a photoshop file~<br>
<br>
Now then, go to painter. I'm using painter 6.1 for this tutorial. It should work with any version of painter, just as long as you can use layers =P Open your PSD file in painter. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.over-protected.net/~katt/pktut/006.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> this is the type of lines we're going to be working with. Super varied line widths always make a piece of lineart look a LOT nicer then a line with just one width. our goal for today is to achiece line 2, not line 1.<br>
<br>
First, make two layers. fill on layer with a solid color that's opposite from what color the sketch is (for example, i'm using a light yellow to go against the blue). This will make the lines you're making a lot easier to see against the darker color. Turn the transparency of that down to between 30% and 50%. The other layer you have created will be for the line art. If you did it, it should look like this:<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.over-protected.net/~katt/pktut/001.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <br>
<br>
Select the GRAPHIC PAINTBRUSH, SOFT under the brushes. I use this rather then the pen tool because it gives a much smoother transition between the thick and thin lines. This is the brush set up I use: <br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.over-protected.net/~katt/pktut/002.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <br>
<br>
start going over the lines of the sketch. it takes a while to get used to going over with the tablet, but it's worth it.<br>
<br>
I hope this has helped some people with the digital inking XD<br>
